Utterances.UttText: Ms Gerry Cage is a 55yoF who presents with a 3 day h/o isolated 6/10 chest pain in the midsternal region that occurred after she lifted heavy bottles from the grocery store to her car.

Phrases.PhraseText: 6/10 chest pain in the midsternal region
heavy bottles from the grocery store

Utterances.UttText: It lasted about 10 minutes and subsided on its own after she rested.
She describes the pain as aching/heavy and not sharp.
She felt faint at the time but otherwise had no other symptoms.
Over the last 4 months, she also reports similar pain but much less intense (described as "flutters" of pain).
She is concerned whether she had an MI.

PHX: HTN - controlled with chlorthalidone/lisinopril SHX: tobacco 1PPD, ETOH weekends: 2-3 drinks, no drugs FHX: father: CAD, died from MI at 40, mother DM2/HTN, died from PE 60  Vitals: BP150/92, p85, RR14, T98F PE:  General: NAD, calm, cooperative Lung: CTAB, no inc WOB Heart: S1/s2 no m/r/g, regular rate/rhythm, no peripheral edema, distal pulses 2+  Ms.
Cage is a 55yoF presenting with an isolated episode of substernal chest pain brought on by increased activity 3 days ago.

Phrases.PhraseText: a 55yoF presenting with an isolated episode of substernal chest pain

Utterances.UttText: Episode likely represented a manifestation of stable angina given relation to activity, family history of CAD/MI, tobacco use, and HTN.

Phrases.PhraseText: a manifestation of stable angina given relation

Utterances.UttText: DDx would include GERD (less likely as it was an isolated episode not coinciding with meals), costochondritis (less likely given lack of tenderness to palpation).

Plan: Establish diagnosis of stable angina/CAD -12 lead EKG -troponin, BMP, CBC, lipid panel, A1c -schedule echocardiograph, stress test, coronary angiography -subsequent Tx to include secondary prevention (statin; LDL<70), ASA, nitrates for breakthrough anginal pain, tight BP control, cessation of smoking

Phrases.PhraseText: diagnosis of stable angina/CAD -12 lead EKG -troponin,
